{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/visualizing-emotions-cec2215e9178", "time": 1683001483.9468958, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/visualizing-emotions-cec2215e9178/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Visualizing Emotions. I wanted to display the emotions of a\u2026 | by Nivedhitha Mathan Kumar | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Visualizing Emotions", "description": "I started by exploring the lexical database, WordNet. My initial idea was to create a graph of all the words (excluding stop-words) connected to their synonyms using WordNet and track the words as it\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://medium.com/@bantic/hand-coding-a-color-wheel-with-canvas-78256c9d7d43", "anchor_text": "Hand-coding a color wheel with canvas", "paragraph_index": 6}, {"url": "http://shortstoriesshort.com/story/hansel-and-gretel/", "anchor_text": "text", "paragraph_index": 6}, {"url": "https://saifmohammad.com/WebPages/AffectIntensity.htm", "anchor_text": "NRC Affect Intensity Lexicon", "paragraph_index": 10}], "all_paragraphs": ["I started by exploring the lexical database, WordNet. My initial idea was to create a graph of all the words (excluding stop-words) connected to their synonyms using WordNet and track the words as it appears on the text. I expected them to create clusters of related words.", "But oops! They were haphazard; I had missed something important. Say, A and B share synsets, and so do B and C. And yet, A and C might have no relation in meaning. For example, a common node connects \u2018take\u2019 and \u2018occupy\u2019. Another node connects \u2018concern\u2019 and \u2018occupy\u2019. This links \u2018take\u2019 and \u2018concern\u2019 even though they do not carry similar meanings.", "The next time, I tried, again using WordNet, to form a tree connected through hypernyms. I tried extending as many leaf nodes as possible to the root \u2018entity\u2019 using derivationally related forms, similar-tos, and verb groups. I used Mike Bostock\u2019s Radial Dendrogram to display the data.", "This time, though it formed clusters, the words were not clustered based on meaning.", "For example, the feelings cluster is placed away from, say, the physical entity cluster. However, within the feelings cluster, the nodes \u2018happy\u2019 and \u2018angered\u2019 are placed close-by. While the two nodes are closely related by hypernyms, they are opposite in meaning.", "Finally, I settled upon the NRC Emotion Intensity Lexicon, aka Affect Intensity Lexicon by Saif M. Mohammad. It contains words scored in the range of 0 to 1 for each of the four emotions: anger, fear, joy, and sadness. I considered 3 of the emotions and used their scores and a color wheel to find their positions.", "To begin with, I took the help of the article Hand-coding a color wheel with canvas by Cory Forsyth. I started with collecting the words of a text that could be found in the lexicon, and their scores. I then scaled each score to the range of 0 to 255 and assigned it a color (green for joy, red for anger, and blue for fear). After converting the RGB value to HSV, I could get its position in a circle from H and S, and value from V.", "Then, using the setTimeout() method, I evaluated the function to draw the SVG elements regularly after an interval. During this interval, with the d3 transition, I could linearly translate between the nodes and transit the color of nodes. But I wanted to create a smoother path; not a linear one.", "So, I created a Catmull-Rom spline using d3 of no stroke or fill and broke it into segments. I then added the data of points along the broken segment to that of each word to use within the setTimeout()\u2019s function.", "Finally, for representing the value V of the HSV color, I changed the radius of the node in proportion to V so it appears to be translating in the direction perpendicular to the screen. Also, to match the background, I overlapped a black circle, of opacity that equals 1-V.", "[1] Saif M. Mohammad, NRC Affect Intensity Lexicon", "This project is my first experiment with Data Visualization and NLP. If you have any feedback or suggestions, mail me at nive.mathan21@gmail.com or let me know in the responses. I\u2019ll be happy to connect!", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "An architect with a keen interest in human-centered design"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fcec2215e9178&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fvisualizing-emotions-cec2215e9178&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fvisualizing-emotions-cec2215e9178&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fvisualizing-emotions-cec2215e9178&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fvisualizing-emotions-cec2215e9178&s